stion":"Which one of the following maternal hormones stimulates placental CRH production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cortisol","Adrenocorticotropic hormone","Prolactin","Progesterone","Oestradiol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPlacental CRH production is uniquely stimulated by maternal \u003Cstrong\u003Ecortisol\u003C/strong\u003E, creating a positive feedback loop. This differs from hypothalamic CRH, which is suppressed by glucocorticoids through negative feedback.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenocorticotropic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E does not directly affect placental CRH production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlactin\u003C/strong\u003E has no direct effect on placental CRH synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone\u003C/strong\u003E does not regulate placental CRH production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestradiol\u003C/strong\u003E is not involved in placental CRH regulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis positive feedback system between maternal cortisol and placental CRH is important for maintaining pregnancy and initiating labour. Placental CRH levels rise exponentially during pregnancy, reaching their peak at delivery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Placental corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) production is uniquely stimulated by cortisol, unlike hypothalamic CRH which is suppressed.","This positive feedback loop between maternal cortisol and placental CRH is crucial for pregnancy progression and labour initiation.","Placental CRH levels increase exponentially throughout pregnancy, reaching their peak at delivery."],"references":["Napso T, Yong HEJ, Lopez-Tello J, Sferruzzi-Perri AN. The Role of Placental Hormones in Mediating Maternal Adaptations to Support Pregnancy and Lactation. Front 